DATA ANALYSIS OF US GUN DATA IN DIFFERENT STATES¶

This analysis would focus on the number of guns sold to the public. The gun_data.xlsx also contains information on private gun sales, gun rentals, pre-pawn, return to seller. However, we wont be looking at these columns for this analysis because of the vast amount of missing data. The amount of missing data is more than half the entire length of the column.

The US census data is a CSV file that contains the population census for each state. There are rows for 2010 population, 2016 population, per capital income, median income and percentage increase in population. Write ups that are not relevant to our analysis are at the base of the file. This would be dropped.

The US census data contains lots of symbols and notations. Extensive data cleaning would be done to rid off these symbols.

The following resources were consulted during the analysis: The pandas API, matplotlip API, numpy API, stackoverflow, geeksforgeeks.

QUESTIONS ANSWERED DURING ANALYSIS¶

This data analysis would answer the following questions:

  • What are the top five states with high gun sales?
  • What are the bottom five states with the least gun sales?
  • What is the likely hood of buying a gun if employed?
  • What census data is associated with high census per capital?
  • Which state have had the highest growth in gun registration?
  • What is the overall trend of gun purchases?
  • How has the population increased over the years?

DATA WRANGLING¶

On assessing the gun_data.xlsx and the us_census_data.csv, we observed that there is a huge amount of missing values on some culumns for the gun data as compared to the amount of rows we have. So, we would drop these columns. I would be using a for loop to drop columns with over 7500 missing values.

Fot the US census data, we would drop the fact_note column and write ups at the base of the dataset would be removed.

Cleaning the gun data set¶

In [11]:
# in a dataset of 12485, I will remove all columns with missing data greater that 7500
# This is for us to have a minimum row of 5000 to work with

for i in df_gun.columns:
    if missing_data[i] > 7500:
        df_gun = df_gun.drop(columns = [i], axis=1)

Convert strings to float and rename columns for the us census data¶

In [20]:
# Lets define a function for renaminng columns
def rename_column(cols):
    
    # replace spaces with underscores and lowercase labels for us census dataset
    cols.rename(columns=lambda x: x.strip().lower().replace(" ", "_"), inplace=True)
    
    return cols.columns # return new names of columns

Lets visualize the total number of guns sold to the public for each state¶

To build this visual, we would be using a bar chart. First, we would use the pandas groupby function to calculate the total number of guns that was bought in each state. Next, we plot a bar chart showing the numbers of guns bought.

From the bar chart plotted, we could see, Texas has the highest numbers of gun bought publicly.

  • The x-axis represent the states while the y-axis represent the numbers of guns sold in millions.
  • Guns sold publicly in Texas from 2010 to 2016 is over 8,000,000 as compared to a population of over 27,000,000 as at 2016. This could mean one in three persons in Texas have a gun including the children population.

Visualizing the class of guns and quantity sold for each class¶

For us to visualize how the classes compare to each other in terms of the one bought the most by Americans, we would be extracting a new dataset called gun_class from our df_gun data. Then we would plot a bar chart to visualize the varying quantities that was bought.

From the bar chart, we could see Americans bought more hand guns.

  • The graph depict the total number of gun class bought by Americans in tens of millions.
  • The x-axis represent the class of gun while the y-axis represent the total number of guns.
  • About 47,000,000 hand guns were bought while about 1.8million represent multiple gun purchase

Lets create a function to visualize relationship between variables using seaborn joint plot¶

In [50]:
def joint_plot(df, xVar, yVar):
    """
    This is a function to define the relationship between 
    two variables using seaborn jointplot
    """
    g = sns.jointplot(x = xVar, y = yVar, data = df, kind = 'reg', line_kws = {'color':'maroon'});
    
    # tidying up labels for x and y axis
    xVar = xVar.replace('_',' ').title()
    yVar = yVar.replace('_',' ').title()
    
    # add main title to the plot
    plt.suptitle(f"Relationship between {yVar} and {xVar}".title(), weight = 'bold', y=1.04);
    
    # set axis labels
    g.set_axis_labels(xVar, yVar)
    
    # set the fig size
    g.fig.set_size_inches(14,6);

Which state have had the highest growth in gun registration?¶

To answer this question, we have to query the permit column to get the total permit issued for each state on the first month of our df_gun dataset and also the total permit issued on the last month. The values gotten for each state on the first month would be substracted from that of the last month. The maximum value gotten would indicate the state that has gotten the highest increase in gun registration.

The state with the highest growth in gun registration is Kentucky as shown by the graph below.

  • The horizontal axis represent states while the y-axis represent permit increase.
  • States like Illinoise and Utah have their number of gun registration drop.

CONCLUSIONS¶

Results: The following deductions can be made from our data

  • The overall trend in gun purchase has increased over the years with a few spikes in 2013 and 2016
  • Kentucky is the state with the highest growth in gun registration with a figure of 194961.0 permits issued
  • High income earners are less likely to purchase a gun publicly, while mid income earners are more likely to purchase a gun from a public source
  • The top five states with the highest number of gun purchase from a public source are Texas, California, Florida, Pennsylvania, Ohio
  • The bottom five states with the least number of gun purchase are Hawaii, Rhode Island, Nebraska, Vermont, Delaware
  • There is a slight indirect relationship between the total number of gun purchased and per capital income earned. The more the per capital income increases, the more the total number of gun purchased publicly reduces.
  • There is a direct relationship between total employment and total gun purchased

Limitations: These are the limimations we experienced during this analysis

  • We do not have enough informations to draw conclusion on the number of guns bought privately
  • We were not able to create any hypothesis or statistical inferences from our data, because the statistics used are descriptive and not inferential
  • We are working with a sample data, which implies uncertainty (a different sample may lead to different results)
  • There were issues with the sample of data: missing observations, data that appears to be inconsistent
